Description_Fewshot.comparison_text:
This Java program checks whether a list of N integers is already sorted in ascending order or can be sorted by exactly one simple operation (a swap of two elements or the reversal of one contiguous segment). It reads N and the array, then scans for “descents” (positions i where p[i] > p[i+1]). 
- If there are no descents, it prints the “already sorted” message.  
- If there is exactly one descent, it tries swapping the two adjacent elements to see if that fixes the sequence;  
- If there are exactly two descents, it tests swapping or reversing the segment that spans from the first descent to the second;  
- For more than two descents it reports that nothing one swap/reverse can sort it.  
All output strings are stored in encrypted form and decrypted at startup via DES, Blowfish, Base64 and simple XOR routines to hide the literal messages.

Description_Reason.comparison_text:
This obfuscated Java program reads two integers a and b, then:
- if a ≤ 5, it sets b to 0;
- else if a ≤ 12, it halves b;
- otherwise leaves b unchanged;
and finally prints b. A nested static `FS` class provides a fast custom scanner for input.

Description_Detailed.comparison_text:
The obfuscated program simply reads three long integers from standard input—let’s call them d (distance), t (time), and s (speed)—and checks whether the vehicle can cover the distance within the given time. Concretely, it tests:

    if (s * t >= d) 
        print “YES”; 
    else 
        print “NO”;

All of the visible complexity (the nested Foster class, multiple decryption routines, static initializers, XOR/DES/Blowfish/Base64 layers, MD5‐derived keys and fancy integer obfuscation) serves only to hide two literal output strings (“YES” and “NO”) and to implement a basic fast I/O wrapper. In reality, no advanced algorithms are used beyond reading tokens, parsing them as longs, doing one 64‐bit multiplication/comparison, and printing the corresponding decrypted message.

Description_Vague.comparison_text:
The obfuscated Java program builds two small integer constants in `Main.I()`: Il[0] = 1 (using `" ".length()`) and Il[1] = 0 (via a pair of nested arithmetic/XOR/& expressions that cancel out). In `main` it then reads two integers `a` and `b` via a custom “FastScanner” class, and initializes `num = 1`, `cnt = 0`. It enters a loop:

  while (num < b) {
    num += (a – 1);
    cnt++;
  }

and finally prints `cnt`. In effect it calculates the smallest `t` such that  
    1 + t·(a–1) ≥ b  
and outputs `t`, which is mathematically `ceil((b–1)/(a–1))`.  

The embedded `FastScanner` is also obfuscated: it allocates a 1024-byte buffer, skips non-printable ASCII (33..126), and parses tokens into `String`, `long`, `int`, or `double`, using hard-coded ASCII codes for ‘-’, ‘0’..’9’ hidden by XOR expressions. There are no other hidden string manipulations—the core logic is simply reading two ints and computing how many increments of size `a–1` are needed to reach or exceed `b` starting from 1.

Description_Detailed.comparison_text:
This small CLI tool reads three integers A, B and C from standard input, then runs a very specific pattern‐matching/counting routine against the constants 5 and 7.  Internally it does this:

1.  Initialize a counter to 0.  
2.  If A is 5 or 7, increment.  
3.  If A==7 and B==5, increment;  
   else if A==5 and B is 5 or 7, increment.  
4.  If A==7 and B==5 and C==5, increment;  
   else if A==5 and B==7 and C==5, increment;  
   else if A==5 and B==5 and C==7, increment.  
5.  If the final count equals 3 (i.e. exactly one of the three “permutations” 7‐5‐5, 5‐7‐5 or 5‐5‐7 was supplied), it prints the first decrypted string (which, once DES‐decrypted at runtime, is “YES”).  Otherwise it prints the second decrypted string, “NO.” (The fancy Base64+XOR/DES routines are just there to hide the literals “YES” and “NO.”)

This is nothing more exotic than an obfuscated “find‐and‐replace” tool.  The inner class hayami is simply a hand‐rolled, byte-level Scanner analogue that reads the next whitespace-delimited token (or number) from System.in.  The Main class hides two very short strings (one used as a regular‐expression, the other as the replacement) by DES-encrypting them with keys derived from the MD5 hashes of “RdohK” and “wnqAc” and then Base64-encoding the cipher text.  At static‐init time Main decrypts those two blobs back into ordinary Java strings (let’s call them pattern P and replacement R).  In main() it does:

    String s = new hayami().nextHayami();
    s = s.replaceAll(P, R);
    System.out.println(s);

and then exits.  All of the index-magic and big constants (MOD, INF, MAX) are vestiges of the obfuscation; the actual runtime behavior is simply to read one token, run a single regex replaceAll, print the result, and quit.

This is an obfuscated Java program whose real job is trivial: it reads three integers a, b and c from standard input, figures out which of the nine possible order‐and‐equality patterns they satisfy (ab>b>c, abbc, a>b==c, a==b==c) and prints a short message for exactly that case. In the clean logic you’d simply write:

  if (ab && b>c) print("strictly decreasing");  
  else if (ac) print("peak");  
  …  
  else if (a==b && b==c) print("all equal");  

Here, each of those nine literal messages is stored in the class as an encrypted Base64 blob (some via XOR+Base64, some via DES, some via Blowfish). At class‐load time a pair of tiny decryption routines (one that does Base64→XOR with a key, another that does Base64→DES or Blowfish with an MD5‐derived key) run to fill a String[]. The main then picks the right array element and prints it. Aside from the heavyweight hiding of the literal text, there is no further twist in the functionality—it’s just a three-number comparator that prints one of nine prewritten lines describing their relation.

This is a heavily obfuscated Java “Hello, World–simple” program that in fact does nothing more exotic than read two integers from standard input and print their product. All literal values (buffer size, zero/one increments, ASCII‐ranges, sign byte, digit bytes, etc.) are hidden in a static int[] ll and computed via bitwise/math tricks in FastScanner.I(). FastScanner wraps System.in in a 1024-byte buffer and provides next(), nextInt(), nextLong(), nextDouble() and array‐reading methods, using ll[2]=1 as the increment step, ll[3]=–1 as the “end‐of‐stream” marker, ll[4]=33…ll[5]=126 to test printability, ll[6]=45 for ‘–’, ll[7]=48…ll[8]=57 for ‘0’–‘9’. In main(), it simply does:  
1. n = sc.nextInt();  
2. a = sc.nextInt();  
3. out.println(n * a);  
4. out.flush();  
No other application logic or hidden strings are present: it’s just integer multiplication.

This program simply reads one token from standard input and checks whether that token contains the character ‘7’.  Internally it uses an obfuscated scanner class (FastScanner) to pull tokens, and three encrypted literals which at runtime decrypt to:
  I[0] = "7"  
  I[1] = "Yes"  
  I[2] = "No"  

In `main` it does:
  String n = sc.next();  
  if (n.contains("7"))  
    System.out.println("Yes");  
  else  
    System.out.println("No");
